        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer215682660" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7606337158134263157">I realize that I&apos;m not the ideal target for this book since I&apos;m much more of a bibliophage than a bibliophile: the library is my favorite place away from home, and I&apos;d be broke if it weren&apos;t. Even so, I’m perplexed by the large number of “loved it” or “it was amazing” reviews. As I struggled through this book, I was reminded of graduate school, the only other place I’ve ever encountered anyone so intent on “one-upping” the rest of the world in terms of the quality and number of books owned or re</span>
  <span id="freeText7606337158134263157" style="display:none">I realize that I'm not the ideal target for this book since I'm much more of a bibliophage than a bibliophile: the library is my favorite place away from home, and I'd be broke if it weren't. Even so, I’m perplexed by the large number of “loved it” or “it was amazing” reviews. As I struggled through this book, I was reminded of graduate school, the only other place I’ve ever encountered anyone so intent on “one-upping” the rest of the world in terms of the quality and number of books owned or read – largely because only in graduate school did I meet with people so insecure about their intellectual status. <br /><br />I'd also like to quibble with the use of the word "common." No matter which definition she's using, Ms. Fadiman seems to be to be taking great pains to present herself as anything but common.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7606337158134263157" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

