</div>

    </div>
  </div>
    <div class="elementListBrownSeparator"></div>



  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3286092497" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3286092497" />
    <a title="Settare (on hiatus)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13198822-settare-on-hiatus"><img alt="Settare (on hiatus)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1590610257p2/13198822.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3286092497?book_show_action=true">Sep 04, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Settare (on hiatus)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Settare (on hiatus)" href="/user/show/13198822-settare-on-hiatus">Settare (on hiatus)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=books-about-books">books-about-books</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=women-writers">women-writers</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=essays">essays</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/13198822-settare-on-hiatus?shelf=american">american</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3286092497" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6327307095397271327"><i>Ex Libris</i> is a collection of eighteen very well-written, witty and sentimental essays about bibliophilia, love of literature and everything <i>&quot;dark academia&quot;</i>, if you will. <br/>Some essays are funny (I chuckled a lot and laughed out loud on more than one occasion), some are boring (I started to read the book in April and gave up on it because I got bored, returned to it nearly half a year later), all of them boast the author&apos;s wits (and vocabulary) and all of them are also overly sentimental. <br/><br/>My person</span>
  <span id="freeText6327307095397271327" style="display:none"><i>Ex Libris</i> is a collection of eighteen very well-written, witty and sentimental essays about bibliophilia, love of literature and everything <i>"dark academia"</i>, if you will. <br />Some essays are funny (I chuckled a lot and laughed out loud on more than one occasion), some are boring (I started to read the book in April and gave up on it because I got bored, returned to it nearly half a year later), all of them boast the author's wits (and vocabulary) and all of them are also overly sentimental. <br /><br />My personal favorite essays are, in order:<br />- <i>"Nothing New Under the Sun"</i>: which is a smart essay on plagiarism.<br />- <i>"The His'er Problem"</i>, which is on the importance of neutralizing language to battle gender bias in the English language (and it was written in the 90s).<br />- <i>"Secondhand Prose"</i> which is about secondhand books (obviously).<br />- <i>“R/      I N S E^ T   A  C A R R O T      E/”</i>, which is on compulsive proofreading (relatable).<br />- <i>"Eternal Ink"</i>, which is about the love of pens, ink, handwriting and penmanship.<br />And finally, her recommended reading. <br /><br />There's also something I didn't like about the book. As much as I enjoyed <i>Ex Libris: Confessions of a Common Reader</i>, I can't appreciate the title. The word <i>"common"</i> is so out of place. It's either meant ironically (I hope), or out of a sheer sense of elitist wilful disregard: I don't know if Ms. Fadiman is aware, but she is certainly not a <i>"common"</i> reader. Her parents were a famous intellectual, author, and editor, and a WWII correspondent and author, she grew up in an elite literary circle, went to Harvard, knows all sorts of influential people (who she randomly even interviewed for this book), she grew up in a home where <i>“Whenever we moved to a new house, a carpenter would build a quarter of a mile of shelves”</i>, and <i>“Our father's library spanned the globe and three millennia, although it was particularly strong in English poetry and fiction of the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries. <u>The only junk, relatively speaking, was science fiction;</u> the only wholly extraliterary works were about wine and cheese. My favorite shelf held the books he had written himself. I liked seeing my own name up there—FADIMAN FADIMAN FADIMAN”.</i> <br />I'm sorry but that makes you a privileged member of the American literary scene, maybe you're a <i>common</i> member of that society, but you're certainly not an average, "common" reader. This can make the book sound quite condescending; I didn't find it so, but I can easily understand why many people would think of Fadiman as an insufferable snob (the comment on Science Fiction being junk?)<br /> So, I wouldn't recommend this to all book lovers. I'd be more likely to only recommend it to Romantics, sentimentalists, lovers of literature and vintage things, those who get nostalgic thinking about the 19th century (<i>good old days</i>), and those who don't mind what can be considered pretentious writing by others.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6327307095397271327" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


